Step 1: Frontend Folder Structure
Let’s assume you want to place the React app inside your project like this:
ecom_project/
├── backend/         # Django backend
└── frontend/        # React frontend (new)

Step 2: Create the React App
Open a new terminal (or deactivate the Django venv) and run:
cd ecom_project
npx create-react-app frontend

cd frontend
npm start


cd E-Commerce-AI-powered-UX-Project/ecom_api/frontend
rm -rf node_modules
npm install
npm start

pip install django-cors-headers
python -m pip install django-cors-headers

cd ecom_project/backend/ecom_api
python manage.py runserver

cd ecom_project/frontend
npm start

Reinstall react-scripts
      npm install react-scripts@5.0.1 --save-dev
      npm start


✅ User Registration

✅ Login to receive a token

✅ Protected endpoints using JWT

✅ Optional: Token refresh/logout

Use double quotes correctly in CMD or PowerShell
Try quoting the full command like this:

& "venv\Scripts\python.exe" -m pip install djangorestframework-simplejwt
Or escape the ampersand:

& 'venv\Scripts\python.exe' -m pip install djangorestframework-simplejwt

Install JWT Authentication
Install Django REST Framework SimpleJWT:
pip install djangorestframework-simplejwt

Install Axios
If you don’t have Axios installed, do so first by running:
npm install axios

Install React Router. Since your code uses <Switch>, we’ll stick with v5:
npm install react-router-dom@5
If you’d prefer the latest v6 API, you can instead run:
npm install react-router-dom

(Optional) Recreate the venv
If you’d rather have a clean, consistently wired environment, you can remove and rebuild it:

powershell
Copy
Edit
# 1. Deactivate venv (if active)
deactivate

# 2. Delete the old venv
Remove-Item -Recurse -Force .\venv

# 3. Recreate it
python -m venv venv

# 4. Activate
.\venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

# 5. Install your packages
python -m pip install django djangorestframework djangorestframework-simplejwt


cd ecom_api
python manage.py startapp accounts


